\iint_S \cfrac{dxdy}{(1+x^{2}+y^{2})^2}
S= (x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^{2}
 x=0
x>0
y=-2, x=-1
0
x \ge 0
-\frac \pi 2 \le \phi \le \frac \pi 2
 x = r\cos \phi \\ y = r\sin \phi 
 \int\int_S \frac {dx\,dy}{\left( 1+ x^2+y^2 \right)^2} = \int_{-\frac \pi 2}^{\frac \pi 2} \int_0^\infty \frac {rdr\,d\phi}{\left( 1+r^2\right)^2} = \frac \pi 2 \int_0^\infty \frac {d \left(r^2+1 \right)}{\left( 1+r^2\right)^2} = -\frac \pi 2 \left .\left(\frac 1{r^2+1} \right) \right|_0^\infty = \\ = -\frac \pi 2 \left( 0 - 1\right) = \frac \pi 2 
\int_0^{\infty} dr\,\frac{r}{(1+r^2)^2} \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} d\theta = \frac{\pi}{2} \int_0^{\infty} du \, \frac{1}{(1+u)^2}=\frac{\pi}{2}
\theta
